---

<BaseLayout
  title="Transfer Conveyors: Right-Angle, 90° & Multi-Directional Transfer Systems"
  description="Transfer conveyors redirect product flow at right angles. Pop-up transfers, chain transfers, turntables, and push diverters compared with speed and load ratings."
  canonical="https://packagingconveyor.com/conveyor-types/transfer-conveyors/"
  schema={[breadcrumbSchema, faqSchema, articleSchema]}
>

  <!-- Breadcrumb -->
  <nav class="bg-surface border-b border-border" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-3">
      <ol class="flex items-center gap-2 text-sm text-ink-muted">
        <li><a href="/" class="hover:text-accent transition-colors">Home</a></li>
        <li class="text-ink-muted/50">/</li>
        <li><a href="/conveyor-types/" class="hover:text-accent transition-colors">Conveyor Types</a></li>
        <li class="text-ink-muted/50">/</li>
        <li class="text-ink font-semibold">Transfer Conveyors</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </nav>

  <!-- AIO -->
  <section class="py-16 sm:py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Transfer Conveyors</div>
      <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase leading-tight mb-8">
        Transfer Conveyors: Right-Angle, 90&deg; & Multi-Directional
      </h1>
      <div class="text-xl text-ink-muted leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        <p>A transfer conveyor changes the direction of product flow between two conveyor lines, typically at a 90-degree (right-angle) intersection. Transfer conveyors include pop-up chain transfers, pop-up ball transfers, right-angle roller chain transfers, turntables, and push diverters. Each type handles different product sizes, weights, and throughput requirements, making transfer technology selection critical for efficient <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">packaging line layouts</a> and distribution system routing.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Transfer Types -->
  <article class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="types-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Transfer Types</div>
      <h2 id="types-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Five Transfer Conveyor <span class="text-accent">Technologies</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Pop-Up Chain Transfer</h3>
        <p>Pop-up chain transfers use parallel chains mounted between the rollers of a <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">roller conveyor</a>. A pneumatic or electric actuator lifts the chains above the roller surface. The chains engage the product bottom and carry it perpendicular to the original direction of travel. When the transfer is not active, the chains retract below the rollers and the product continues straight on the roller conveyor.</p>
        <p>Pop-up chain transfers handle products from 10 to 300 lbs at speeds of 30-120 FPM. Transfer cycle time is typically 2-4 seconds (lift, transfer, lower). The product maintains its orientation throughout the transfer. Hytrol, Dematic, and Intelligrated offer pop-up chain transfer modules that integrate with their roller conveyor platforms. Pop-up chains work best with flat-bottomed cases and cartons that span at least 2 chain strands.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Pop-Up Ball Transfer</h3>
        <p>Pop-up ball transfers use a grid of ball transfer units (omnidirectional ball bearings) mounted between rollers. When the balls rise above the roller surface, the product rides on the ball field and can be pushed or guided in any direction , not limited to 90 degrees. Pop-up ball transfers suit light products (under 75 lbs) and are used where multi-directional routing is needed from a single transfer point.</p>
        <p>Ball transfers provide the most routing flexibility but the least positive drive. They rely on external pushers, guide rails, or downstream conveyors to pull the product in the desired direction. They are slower than chain transfers and less suitable for high-throughput applications.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Right-Angle Roller Chain Transfer</h3>
        <p>A right-angle roller chain transfer is a dedicated section with perpendicular chain-driven rollers that transfer product at 90 degrees. Unlike pop-up units that lift above existing rollers, the right-angle transfer section has its own set of rollers oriented at 90 degrees to the incoming line. The product enters on the infeed rollers, stops, and the perpendicular rollers engage to carry the product sideways onto the discharge conveyor.</p>
        <p>Right-angle roller chain transfers handle heavy loads (up to 4,000 lbs for pallet applications) and provide reliable positive drive throughout the transfer. <a href="/conveyor-types/cdlr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">CDLR conveyor</a> systems commonly use right-angle chain transfers for <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/pallet/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">pallet routing</a>.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Turntable Transfer</h3>
        <p>A turntable transfer rotates the entire conveyor section (and the product on it) to change direction. The product enters the turntable section, the section physically rotates 90, 180, or any angle, and the product exits in the new direction. Turntables handle the heaviest loads (up to 10,000 lbs for pallet turntables) but have the slowest cycle time (6-10 seconds per transfer).</p>
        <p>Turntable transfers excel in pallet handling where pop-up mechanisms cannot support the load. They also serve applications where the product must be rotated (not just redirected) , for example, rotating a pallet 90 degrees for stretch wrapping or rotating a case for label application on a different face.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Push Diverter</h3>
        <p>A push diverter uses a pneumatic or electric actuator to push the product off the main conveyor line onto a perpendicular spur. The simplest designs use a flat pusher plate. More sophisticated versions use angled paddles or sweep arms that guide the product at an angle rather than a sudden perpendicular push. Push diverters handle line speeds up to 200 FPM and work with products from 1 to 100 lbs.</p>
        <p>Push diverters cost less than pop-up transfers but can rotate the product during the push, which is unacceptable for orientation-sensitive products. They also generate more product impact force. Push diverters are common in <a href="/conveyor-functions/reject-systems/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">reject systems</a> where failed QC products are pushed off the main line.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- Comparison Table -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="comparison-heading">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
